      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T14:35:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not sure this is going to be a usable long-term approach. Containers are probably the biggest reason to adopt absl (IMO), and internally they reference mutexes, which will pull in dynamic annotations. (They don\u0027t use mutexes for basic operations. It\u0027s for things like hashtablez/, which we don\u0027t need, but unfortunately they still pull in the #includes.)\n\nI would try adding flat_hash_map to your example CL. When I tried it, the dependency graph got much larger in a hurry.\n\nIf this prevents us from using the containers entirely, I\u0027d think that\u0027s a fatal blow for absl adoption. At least for me, I don\u0027t see it as worth all this effort if we\u0027re not going to get the containers.\n\nBTW, what\u0027s the rationale specifically for calling out \"absl::Mutex\" as a type to avoid? Does it break something too?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "2e6e8b853eeb43bf75ad331b6bcea58f66ed1dea",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6c396795_0a15c4f5",
        "filename": "third_party/absl/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T14:48:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, if the containers depend on absl::Mutex or dynamic_annotations, then this is fatal.  I\u0027d double check that, because if a container data structure really depends on absl::Mutex or dynamic_annotations, then that\u0027s an indication of poor design and a second reason to not use absl.\n\nabsl::Mutex is a crutch for Google3 developers used to its pre-standard behavior.  We already have to think about SkMutex, SkSharedMutex, SkSpinlock, std::mutex, inevitably std::shared_mutex, and often our clients\u0027 own locking abstractions... I will not allow any more that don\u0027t start \"std::\".",
      "parentUuid": "0ccba309_f7029d1e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "2e6e8b853eeb43bf75ad331b6bcea58f66ed1dea",
