      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T15:49:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "BTW re\n\u003c\u003c\nIt absolutely is poor design to require a data structure to depend on a global statistic sampling system.  This whole feature is ancillary and requiring it and its dependencies will hurt the adoption of what is otherwise a very good data structure.\n\u003e\u003e\nThat is not the case.\n\nThe data structure can POTENTIALLY use a global statistic sampling system, which results in a #include which ends up #including Mutex.\n\nGoogle3 frowns on forward declarations for Reasons. (http://go/cstyle#Forward_Declarations) In absence of this guidance, the easy fix here would be to break the #include chain via forward declaration. \n\nI am not sure we would get traction with the argument of \"we want to use bits and pieces of absl, so please accept this patch which replaces an #include with a forward declaration\" because fundamentally I expect they would not be supportive of partial adoption. (At least, it is unlikely that they would want to support it, and we would be exposed to the possibility of future breakage at any time.)",
      "parentUuid": "4f8a9b95_d4e6602f",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "2e6e8b853eeb43bf75ad331b6bcea58f66ed1dea",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c0a930f0_7cf90dfd",
        "filename": "third_party/absl/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T16:08:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think maybe we\u0027re just misunderstanding each other\u0027s vocabulary.  Bottom line, any need to build hashtablez, absl::Mutex, or dynamic_annotations.cc is a deal breaker.  (dynamic_annotations.cc you can fix externally with #defines, but without doing that, it\u0027s no good.)\n\nThe Google3 style guide also often offers bad advice and is not always definitive when writing Skia code.  In this case of the article on forward declarations, I agree on almost everything they say except perhaps the likelihood and severity of the cons.  I don\u0027t read that decisions section as frowning on forward declarations at all... it\u0027s a very practical balance that allows lots of sensible forward declaration and steers you away from places where it makes more of a mess than it helps.\n\nBreaking the dependency via refactoring, whether a forward declaration, a #define flag, or something else sounds great to me.  Do you want to try this?  If you are afraid to ask Abseil I don\u0027t mind.\n\nIf by using Abseil we\u0027re exposing ourselves to future breakage, we need to undo this now and drop the idea forever.  We do follow the rules here (https://abseil.io/about/compatibility) right?  and are thus covered by their 5 year support and API compatibility?",
      "parentUuid": "6a71834e_e3c327bb",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "2e6e8b853eeb43bf75ad331b6bcea58f66ed1dea",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d9f56951_3afb5be2",
        "filename": "third_party/absl/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T21:58:47Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003c\u003c We do follow the rules here (https://abseil.io/about/compatibility) right? \u003e\u003e\n\nWell, there is a big caveat in the rules:\n\n\"We may make changes to the internal #include graph for Abseil headers - if you use an API, please include the relevant header file directly.\"\n\nHypothetically, this exposes us to the hypothetical risk that at any time, their include graph may expose us to the Mutex header, the dynamic-annotations header, or some other header that we did not intend to use.\n\nIf we have hard lines on Abseil headers which we must not include, and these rules are not agreed upon by the Abseil team, then it seems like we\u0027d potentially be at risk at all times. It seems precarious to me.\n\nThe hashtablez case is a great example of this kind of concern IMO. What if the btree_map suddenly gets similar diagnostic abilities? We can\u0027t guarantee that this won\u0027t happen. We could certainly work around it if it happens--it\u0027s not a showstopper--but in general it seems like a not-great position to be in.",
      "parentUuid": "c0a930f0_7cf90dfd",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "2e6e8b853eeb43bf75ad331b6bcea58f66ed1dea",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "730686c3_b700b9b1",
        "filename": "third_party/absl/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-30T22:02:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, I think I reluctantly agree.  If there are parts of Abseil we don\u0027t want present, I don\u0027t see a way to enforce that.  They could certainly refactor dynamic_annotations.cc to some other file that we\u0027re building and then we\u0027d be horked again.\n\nThis is largely why we don\u0027t require third_party dependencies.  We cannot trust them and have no control over their future behavior.",
      "parentUuid": "d9f56951_3afb5be2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 11,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 13,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "2e6e8b853eeb43bf75ad331b6bcea58f66ed1dea",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a0810999_aeb5b52b",
        "filename": "third_party/absl/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 13,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-01T12:27:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003c\u003c If there are parts of Abseil we don\u0027t want present, I don\u0027t see a way to enforce that. \u003e\u003e\n\nThere are a couple of different ways to approach it. \n\nOne way that I don\u0027t recommend but will list for completeness\u0027 sake--make an Skia-specific absl fork, and remove the stuff we don\u0027t like. This is an ironclad guarantee that we get what we want and nothing else, but also deprives us of improvements and bugfixes going forward. Again, I am not advocating for this as in the long term I think it ends up being a boondoggle.\n\nAnother way that seems plausible to me: fix dynamic_annotations properly with the appropriate defines (this one seems like a particularly deep-rooted special case), and simply allow absl to internally include its own headers like Mutex as needed. Disallow direct usage of absl::Mutex anywhere within Skia; potentially, disallow any absl feature which internally leverages Mutex (if such a ban is beneficial to us--not sure about this point). \"Disallow\" can be as simple as a written-down policy enforced by vigorous code review, or can be as thorough as a Gerrit presubmit check (https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/Documentation/dev-plugins.html#pre-submit-evaluator) that prevents the string \"absl::Mutex\" from appearing in the code. \n\nI am the rookie here for sure, but it seems to me that a policy document on the Skia website saying \"Skia only allows the following absl modules to be used\" (or the inverse, \"Skia disallows the following absl modules\") would be sufficient to keep us on the straight and narrow. If absl internally #includes the mutex header in some deep chain of #includes, that shouldn\u0027t affect us directly; it\u0027ll get dead-stripped as long as it\u0027s not used anyway. In the event that someone accidentally adds absl::Mutex to our code base, AND it slips past a reviewer, we can just revert it or convert to SkMutex.\n\nIf we are willing to do macro shenanigans in our absl build files, we might even be able to rename Mutex within absl to \"BANNED_Mutex\" or something. This would make it extraordinarily unlikely to leak into Skia, but I also think it\u0027s probably overkill and might cause its own set of problems to solve. Personally I think review vigilance should be sufficient.\n\nThere are probably other ways to approach the problem as well. This seems like a very solvable problem to me, as long as the team is on board and code reviewers know what to look for, and we assume good intentions from all involved.",
      "parentUuid": "730686c3_b700b9b1",
